<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
  <chapter xml:id="ch-function-factories" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Function Factories</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        A <em>function factory</em> is a function that makes functions. Here's
        a very simple example: we use a function factory (<c>power1()</c>) to
        make two child functions (<c>square()</c> and <c>cube()</c>):
      </p>

      <program language="r">
        <input>
power1 &lt;- function(exp) {
  function(x) {
    x ^ exp
  }
}

square &lt;- power1(2)
cube &lt;- power1(3)
        </input>
      </program>

      <p>
        Don't worry if this doesn't make sense yet, it should by the end of
        the chapter!
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <section xml:id="sec-factory-fundamentals">
      <title>Factory fundamentals</title>

      <p>
        The key idea that makes function factories work can be expressed
        concisely, but requires a bit of background: function factories work
        because of first-class functions and lexical scoping.
      </p>
    </section>

  </chapter>
